          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">And yet, perhaps th=
e most sweeping tech-related question facing Congress is what guardrails to=
 put on artificial intelligence and cryptocurrency. A.I. is a unique source=
 of bipartisanship, and at least two on-the-rise senators on Commerce=E2=80=
=94incoming Senate Majority leader <b>John Thune</b> and senior committee D=
emocrat <b>Amy Klobuchar=E2=80=94</b>paired up last term to introduce a bil=
l that would call for A.I. companies to be transparent about what is and is=
 not real online. <br/><br/>As for crypto, the sector has <i>many </i>new f=
riends on Capitol Hill. Three crypto-aligned super PACs=E2=80=94the biparti=
san =E2=80=9CFairshake,=E2=80=9D the Republican =E2=80=9CDefend American Jo=
bs,=E2=80=9D and the Democratic =E2=80=9CProtect Progress=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94=
spent a combined <i>$133,000,000</i> last cycle, according to the Center fo=
r Responsive Politics. The top three donors for each arm were Andreessen
Horowitz, Coinbase, and Ripple. In all, the three super PACs cash deluge he=
lped elect seven senators (three Democrats, four Republicans) and 49 House =
members (29 Democrats and 20 Republican). The next Congress will show just =
how much sway Bitcoin can buy. <br/><br/><i>And now, a little bit more on h=
ow the A.I. debate is playing out on Capitol Hill, courtesy of my recent co=
nversation with Baratunde Thurston=E2=80=A6</i><br/></td>
